    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Number of ACA staff trained on international anti-corruption standards with focus on prevention of corruption. 
2. Number of Institutions equipped with effective anti-corruption tools.</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2021">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. 0
2. 0</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. 20 (at least 20% women)
2. 1</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. The Project has organized jointly with UNDP PCEAT project professional advanced training for the entire staff of the Anti-Corruption Agency on the study of the specifics of the International standards for anti-corruption management systems according to ISO 37001: 2016 &#x201C;Anti-Bribery (Anticorruption) management system&#x201D;. As a result, 55 employees received the certificate of completion, among which 14 women (25%). Besides, in order to strengthen the role of civil society and the media, increase the knowledge of non-governmental organizations, journalists and social activists in combating corruption, the project organized a special training on the topic: &#x201C;The role of interaction with the public in combating corruption&#x201D; for NGOs and the media, which was attended by representatives of more 35 NGOs and 25 media outlets. The training specifically focused on the role and interests of groups most vulnerable to corruption, such as women, youth, people with disabilities, the elderly, etc.

2. Project has directly equipped the Anticorruption Agency with several anticorruption tools, including mobile app &#x201C;Anticorruption&#x201D;, which empowers citizens to report corruption cases, and the new digital informational resource &#x2013; &#x201C;Uzbekistan Anticorruption e-Digest&#x201D;, which aims to inform the public on ongoing anticorruption reforms in country and provide platform for discussing challenges and problems in the field. 

Besides, according to the Annual Work Plan, the Project supported the Anti-Corruption Agency in the development of a draft strategic comprehensive document - the National Anti-Corruption Strategy for 2021-2025. For this, the project with partners were involved in the designing process. Four respective Round Tables on National Discussions (in January, in February, in March, in April) were organized for discussion of the draft with a wide range of stakeholders, including government officials, civil society organizations, non-governmental organizations of a different nature, mass media and Internet bloggers, social media activists, scientific and educational circles, international development organizations and donor communities, etc. UNDP Global Anticorruption Program and IRH have contributed with the technical and advisory support, with providing the international standards, good foreign practices, exemplary alternatives. The Project experts directly developed several chapters of the draft Strategy, which were included in the final version. The draft Strategy has been submitted for consideration and signing by the countrys leadership.
The project played an important role in establishing international relations of the Anti-Corruption Agency, providing, upon their request, translation and other logistics for their meetings with partners and anti-corruption agencies of other countries, webinars and trainings.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
